{{Cquote| The protector of the three worlds, the child R<U+0101>ma asks Kausaly<U+0101> with great inquisitiveness, <U+201C>Whence the darkness in the moon?<U+201D> The mother says, <U+201C>A [[blackbuck]] has entered the moon, afraid of your arrows.<U+201D> R<U+0101>ma says, <U+201C>Not thus, mother. I slay only the deer in the disguise ([[Maricha|M<U+0101>r<U+012B>ca]]) <U+2013> whose delusion is renowned, and no other.<U+201D> Kausaly<U+0101> says, <U+201C>[[Prithvi|P<U+1E5B>thv<U+012B>]] has gone into the moon out of the fear of R<U+0101>va<U+1E47>a, which is the darkness seen in the moon.<U+201D> R<U+0101>ma says, <U+201C>How can the [[Chandra|Candra]], himself afraid of [[Rahu|R<U+0101>hu]] protect someone, surely P<U+1E5B>thv<U+012B> is not naive.<U+201D> Kausaly<U+0101> then says <U+201C>You saw the moon to be similar to the face of your bride, hence you have entered the moon to kiss your wife, and hence the moon appears dark.<U+201D> R<U+0101>ma says, <U+201C>No mother, its only your milk that I drink, so how is the moon dark?<U+201D> On hearing this, the queen smiled and the speech of Giridhara was amazed. <U+0965> 1.3.6 <U+0965>}}
</blockquote>

